9 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4.4. (a) This section applies to a request for a
10 record that the public agency considers to be excepted from disclosure
11 under section 4(b)(1) or 4(b)(25) of this chapter. The public agency
12 may do either of the following:
13 (1) Deny disclosure of the record or a part of the record. The
14 person requesting the information may appeal the denial under
15 section 9 of this chapter.
16 (2) Refuse to confirm or deny the existence of the record,
17 regardless of whether the record exists or does not exist, if the fact
18 of the record's existence or nonexistence would reveal information
19 that would:
20 (A) impede or compromise an ongoing law enforcement
21 investigation or result in danger to an individual's safety,
22 including the safety of a law enforcement officer or a
23 confidential source; or
24 (B) reveal information that would have a reasonable likelihood
25 of threatening public safety.
26 (b) This subsection applies to a request for a record that the public
27 agency considers to be excepted from disclosure under section 4(b)(19)
28 of this chapter. The agency may consult with the governor's security
29 council established by IC 10-19-8.1-2 in formulating a response. The
30 public agency may do either of the following:
31 (1) Deny disclosure of the record or a part of the record. The
32 agency or the counterterrorism and security council shall provide
33 a general description of the record being withheld and of how
34 disclosure of the record would have a reasonable likelihood of
35 threatening public safety by exposing a vulnerability to terrorist
36 attack. The person requesting the information may appeal the
37 denial under section 9 of this chapter.
38 (2) Refuse to confirm or deny the existence of the record
39 regardless of whether the record exists or does not exist, if the fact
40 of the record's existence or nonexistence would reveal information
41 that would have a reasonable likelihood of threatening public
42 safety.
